US-China tech war.
The disastrous diplomatic policy decisions made by the previous generation of Americans (and even those of earlier generations) originating from New York are the 2003 US invasion of Iraq, which was referred to as the "war of choice," purportedly aimed at eliminating – in reality, nonexistent – weapons of mass destruction.
Understanding the necessity of grasping the flawed logic behind this disastrous decision has become unprecedentedly pressing, as the same logic is now being invoked to justify similar misguided US policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then-US Vice President Richard Cheney, who claimed that even if the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists was small (for example, 1 percent), we should take action as if this were an inevitable scenario.
This line of reasoning almost always leads to wrong decisions.
However, the US and some of its allies are now using Cheneyism to attack China's technology.
According to the US government, since we cannot confirm that China's technology is secure, we should approach and ban it as if it is inevitably harmful.
Correct decisions will apply probability estimates to alternative options.
One generation ago, US policymakers should have considered not only the (claimed) 1% risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists, but also the 99% risk of launching a war based on multiple flawed premises.
By simply emphasizing that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) diverted public attention and caused people to overlook the fact that the Iraq war lacked legitimacy and would severely destabilize the Middle East and global politics.
The problem with Cheneyism, however, lies not only in its tendency to act on small risks without considering the extremely high potential costs, but also in politicians' tendency to whip up fear for some unknown purposes.
This is what US leaders are doing again: stoking panic about Chinese tech companies by pointing to and exaggerating some tiny risks.
One of the most relevant cases, although not the only one, is the US government's attack on Huawei, a communications technology company.
The US is gradually shutting down the company's domestic market and is working to strangle its global business.
Like Iraq, the US may ultimately cause a completely unwarranted geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have long been paying attention to the technological advancements made by Huawei, because I believe that 5G and other digital technologies can provide a huge driving force for eradicating poverty and achieving other UN Sustainable Development Goals.
I have also had similar interactions with other telecommunications companies, and I have encouraged the industry to take action towards achieving the sustainable development goals.
I have written a brief foreword for a report on this topic prepared by Huawei on a volunteer basis and was subsequently criticized by anti-China zealots. I have asked industry leaders and government officials if there is any evidence that Huawei has engaged in any unseemly behavior, and I repeatedly received the answer that Huawei's conduct is no different from that of other trustworthy industry leaders.
Despite this, the US government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment could pose a threat to global security.
US officials claim that the "backdoors" Huawei software or hardware may have left could allow the Chinese government to conduct surveillance globally.
They point out that Chinese law requires Chinese companies to cooperate with the government on national security grounds.
The facts are right before our eyes.
Huawei's 5G equipment is priced affordably and of high quality, currently leading many competitors and already being promoted.
Its high performance stems from massive investments in research and development over many years, economies of scale, and the baptism by fire in the Chinese digital market.
Considering the crucial importance of this technology to their sustainable development, it would be unwise for low-income economies around the world to reject the early rollout of 5G.
Despite a lack of evidence of any backdoor existing, the US is still lobbying the world to distance itself from Huawei.
US claims are universal.
As one US Federal Communications Commissioner put it: " Nations that have 5G will have related innovation and set standards for the rest of the world, and that nation is unlikely to be the US."
Other nations — particularly the UK — have yet to find any backdoor in Huawei's hardware and software.
Even if a backdoor is discovered in the future, it can almost certainly be closed at that time.
The debate about Huawei is also raging in Germany, as the US government has threatened to reduce intelligence cooperation unless authorities block Huawei's 5G technology.
Perhaps under US pressure, the head of Germany's Federal Intelligence Service recently made a declaration similar to Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not a field suitable for a group that cannot be fully trusted to engage in."
And he has not produced any concrete evidence of wrongdoing.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel has been quietly fighting for Huawei to be allowed onto the market.
But ironically, America's complaints actually reflect America's own surveillance activities at home and abroad – although this is hardly news.
Chinese devices may make it harder for the US government to implement secret surveillance.
However, any government's unjustified surveillance activities should cease.
The UN's independent oversight efforts aimed at reducing such activities should be part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should choose diplomacy and institutional safeguards over fighting a technological war.
The US's threat to ban Huawei goes beyond the early adoption of 5G networks, posing a significant risk to rule-based trade systems.
Today, the US is no longer the uncontested leader in global technology, and US President Trump and his advisors are unwilling to engage in competition based on a rule-based system.
Their goal is to curb China's technological rise.
They are simultaneously attempting to undermine the World Trade Organization by crippling its dispute settlement mechanism, which also reflects their pattern of disregard for global rules.
If the Trump administration succeeds in "succeeding" in dividing the world into separate technological camps, the risk of future conflicts will increase exponentially.
